	wordHeading={`His Word will not return void`}
	wordBodyHtml={`<p>Maybe you don't feel any different after reading a verse. That's okay. God's Word is like a seed planted in good soil — it grows quietly, even when you can't see it. The truth that you are loved will take root in you and hold you steady, long after the hard middle-school days are behind you.</p><p class="mt-4" style="color: var(--color-ink);">"My word… will not return to me empty, but will accomplish that which I purpose." <span style="color: var(--color-muted);">— Isaiah 55:11</span></p>`}
	fatherSaysHeading={`What your Father says over you`}
	fatherSaysHtml={`<p>"My child, I know middle school is hard. I see the lunch table, the group chat you're not in, the comment that hurt. I see you scrolling and feeling like everyone else is enough and you're not. So let Me tell you the truth: you <em>are</em> enough — because you are Mine.</p><p>I made every part of you on purpose. I wasn't having an off day when I made you — I made you fearfully and wonderfully, and I love who you are. I don't look at your face or your followers; I look at your heart, and I treasure it. You don't have to be the funniest or the most popular or the prettiest to be loved by Me. You already are, all the way, today.</p><p>When you're anxious, I'm right beside you. When you feel left out, you are never left out of My love — nothing in the whole world can separate you from it. You belong to Me. I sing over you. And every single morning when you wake up, I want you to know: you are My beloved child, and I am so glad you're Mine."</p>`}
	prayerHeading={`A prayer for middle schoolers`}
	prayerHtml={`<p>Our Father, we thank You and praise You for these middle schoolers. Let them hear Your whisper above all their noise — the comparison, the pressure to fit in, and the voices online that tell them they're not enough. Let them encounter Your love — not as a rule, but as a Father's delight — and know they are Your beloved, apart from their looks, their grades, or how many friends they have.</p><p>Give them grace to receive their identity from You before the world tells them who to be. Father, steady their hearts in these changing years — when they feel left out, remind them they belong to You; when they feel weird or unseen, remind them You made them on purpose and call them wonderful. I pray Your protection over them from the enemy, from temptation, from bullying and cruelty, from everything harmful online, and from despair.</p><p>Let them know there is no condemnation in You, that they are fearfully and wonderfully made, and that nothing can separate them from Your love. Let them know You, their Father, as their true home and reward. And may they wake up every single day knowing they are loved by their heavenly Father.</p><p>In Jesus' name, amen.</p>`}
